    ],
    "steps_detailed": [
      "Marinate the chicken in the yogurt, garlic, ginger, chili powder, and turmeric for at least 30 minutes, or overnight for real depth.",
      "Fry half the onion in the oil over medium heat, stirring often, 10-12 minutes, until deeply browned and crisp - these fried onions (birista) are a defining biryani garnish and flavor, not a decoration; set aside half for the top.",
      "Brown the marinated chicken with the remaining onion in the same oil, 8-10 minutes, along with the cardamom and cinnamon.",
      "Parboil the basmati separately in well-salted water 5-6 minutes, until still quite firm in the center, then drain.",
      "Layer the parboiled rice over the chicken in the pot, drizzle with the saffron milk, scatter with the reserved fried onions and cilantro, cover tightly (a layer of foil under the lid helps seal in the steam), and cook over very low heat 20-25 minutes.",
      "Rest 5 minutes off the heat before gently folding the layers together to serve.",
      "This is the actual dum technique biryani is built on - parboiled rice steamed on top of already-cooked meat under a tight seal, letting the two layers finish together while staying distinct, rather than being cooked as one pot of seasoned rice from the start. The marinated yogurt, fried onions, and layered steaming are what separate real biryani from a spiced pilaf; skipping any of them changes what the dish actually is."
    ]
